The Public Use Natality File Data Analysis

Created by Yifei Kang (yifeik3)

Import the 2015 US Natality Data using an R code chunk and the data URL https://uofi.box.com/shared/static/2dj9jcv0cwrz2l5d5ubu2msje0bqt5wo.csv.

The dataset (.csv) contains 200000 observations and 22 columns and represents less than 5% of the entire data available. The observations are registered births in the United States for year 2015 with various measures about the mother, the child(ren) she birthed, and their health outcomes including pre- and post-partum care. Specifically, the columns are MAGER, FAGECOMB, MEDUC, MRACEHISP, ILP_R, PRECARE, PREVIS, WIC, CIG_0, CIG_1, CIG_2, CIG_3, M_HT_IN, BMI, PWGT_R, DWGT_R, WTGAIN, APGAR5, DPLURAL, SEX, DBWT, and BFED. The original source is the National Vital Statistics System (NVSS), a component of the Center for Disease Control and Preventions (CDC) National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS) https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/nvss/births.htm. The data User Guide is quite helpful for understanding the variables and their values.

Now, print the descriptor portion of the data.

#1. Problem Is there a gender preference of baby in each race? What is the percentage of each gender in different mother races

#1. Plan Count the number of newborns of each gender within race, calculate and compare the percentage of genders

#1. Data and Analysis Select column of mother race (MRACEHISP), and gender of the infant (SEX), then draw graph of each gender percentage in each mother race

data_1 <- data %>%
  select(MRACEHISP, SEX) %>%
  mutate(Race=recode(MRACEHISP,"1" = "White", "2" = "Black", "3" = "AIAN", "4" = "Asian", "5" = "NHOPI", "6" = "More than one race", "7" = "Hispanic", "8" = "Origin unknown or not stated")) %>%
  group_by(Race,SEX) %>%
  summarise(frequencies=n()) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(percents = round(frequencies/sum(frequencies),3))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'Race' (override with `.groups` argument)
data_1

ggplot(data = data_1, aes(x = Race, y = percents, fill = SEX, label = percents*100)) + 
  geom_col() +
  geom_text(size = 4, position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), fontface = "bold")+
  coord_flip() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)

#1. Conclusion Although the number of female and male newborns differs among races, the percentages of female and male are about the same, with overall 49% female and 51% male. The only exception is NHOPI (Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander), which has 51.6% of female and 48.4% of male

#2. Problem Which race has the highest percentage of mother that has been educated for bachelors degree or higher? Which race has the lowest percentage?

#2. Plan Count and compare the ratio of mother education degree (MEDUC) among different races.

#2. Data and Analysis Assign the respective level of race its actual names. Assign degree levels of MEDUC with level 6, 7, and 8 with Bachelors degree or higher, and the rest of the degrees with Other. Count the number of the two levels, and calculate the percentage within each race. Draw the bar graph according to the percentage levels

data_2 <- data %>%
  select(MEDUC,MRACEHISP) %>%
  mutate(Race=recode(MRACEHISP, "1" = "White", "2" = "Black", "3" = "AIAN", "4" = "Asian", "5" = "NHOPI", "6" = "More than one race", "7" = "Hispanic", "8" = "Origin unknown or not stated"), Edu=recode(MEDUC,"6"="Bachelors degree or higher","7" = "Bachelors degree or higher", "8" = "Bachelors degree or higher", "1" = "Other", "2" = "Other", "3" = "Other", "4" = "Other", "5" = "Other", "9" = "Other")) %>%
  group_by(Race,Edu) %>%
  summarise(frequencies=n()) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(percents = round(frequencies/sum(frequencies),4))

#3. Problem Does the education level of mother affect the birth weight of the baby?

#3. Plan Compare with birth weight of the baby with different educational level of the mother

#3. Data and Analysis Remove invalid data with birth weight (DBWT) value of 9999. Assign the respective level of MEDUC its actual names. Draw graph of average DBWT for visualization, run LSD comparison by the educational level of mothers

data_3 <- data %>%
  select(MEDUC, DBWT) %>%
  filter(DBWT<9999)%>%
  mutate(Edu=recode(MEDUC,"1" = "8th grade or less", "2" = "9th through 12th grade with no diploma", "3" = "High school graduate or GED completed", "4" = "Some college credit, but not a degree", "5" = "Associate degree","6"="Bachelors degree","7" = "Masters degree", "8" = "Doctorate or Professional Degree", "9" = "Unknown")) %>%
  group_by(Edu)

Table_3 <- summarise(data_3, Weight=mean(DBWT))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
Table_3
## # A tibble: 9 x 2
##   Edu                                    Weight
##   <chr>                                   <dbl>
## 1 8th grade or less                       3246.
## 2 9th through 12th grade with no diploma  3180.
## 3 Associate degree                        3297.
## 4 Bachelors degree                       3343.
## 5 Doctorate or Professional Degree        3308.
## 6 High school graduate or GED completed   3218.
## 7 Masters degree                         3331.
## 8 Some college credit, but not a degree   3272.
## 9 Unknown                                 3229.
Table_3 %>%
  mutate(Education = fct_reorder(Edu, desc(Weight))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Education, y=Weight)) +
  coord_flip() +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width=0.7, fill="steelblue") +
  geom_text(aes(label=round(Weight, digits=1)), color="white", size=3.5,hjust=1.2, fontface = "bold")

ggplot(data = data_3, aes(x=Edu, y=DBWT)) +
  coord_flip() +
  geom_boxplot()

lm <- lm(DBWT~Edu, data=data_3)
out <- LSD.test (lm, "Edu" ,p.adj="bonferroni")
par(mar=c(4,16,4,4))
plot(out, main = "Newborn weight", xlab="Weight(g)",las=1,horiz=T)

#3. Conclusion There are significant differences on birth weight among difference educational level of mothers. The average birth weight is highest in mother with bachelors degree, which is 3342.5g. The lowest average birth weight is in mother with 9th through 12th grade with no diploma, which is 3179.6g. Overall, the birth weight of baby is higher in mother with bachelors degree or higher

#4. Problem Suppose we want to model baby birth weight in gram (DBWT) using MEDUC, MAGER, PREVIS, BMI, WTGAIN as predictors in a linear regression with model selection. How well does the final model fit?

#4. Plan Use DBWT as response variable. Proceed with the linear regression modeling strategy (employing the model selection approaches). Create a table showing the final chosen regression model estimates. Interpret the model results.

#4. Data and Analysis Remove invalid data with birth weight (DBWT) value of 9999. Run the glm and select appropreate model

data_4 <- data %>%
  select(DBWT, MEDUC, MAGER, PREVIS, BMI, WTGAIN) %>%
  filter(DBWT<9999)
#Detect multicollinearity
car::vif(lm(DBWT ~ MEDUC + MAGER + PREVIS + BMI + WTGAIN, data=data_4))

comps <- leaps::regsubsets(DBWT ~ MEDUC + MAGER + PREVIS + BMI + WTGAIN, data=data_4, nbest=2)
plot(comps,scale="adjr2") #AdjustedRsquare chosen model is: MEDUC + MAGER + PREVIS + BMI + WTGAIN

plot(comps,scale="bic") #BIC chosen model is: MEDUC + MAGER + WTGAIN

plot(comps,scale="Cp") #Cp chosen model is: MEDUC + MAGER + PREVIS + BMI + WTGAIN

lin2 <- glm(DBWT ~  MEDUC + MAGER + WTGAIN, data=data_4, family="gaussian")

#4. Conclusion VIF threshold of 10 is not violated, so I will not remove any predictors based on multicollinearity. There is no missing values. AIC chosen model is MEDUC + MAGER + PREVIS + BMI + WTGAIN. Automatic selection chosen model agree with AIC model except for BIC chosen model is MEDUC + MAGER + WTGAIN. When comparing the two models, although BIC chosen model had a slightly higher RMSE and lower R-squared value, the differences of these values are minimal, and the AIC only increased for 6, BIC model has 2 less predictors compared with AIC model. Therefore, I will chose the BIC chosen model with MEDUC + MAGER + WTGAIN. This model has RMSE=585.58 AIC=3115147 and adjusted R-squared=0.022, it is a poor fit model. Because we would prefer to have a high R-square and low RMSE, and low AIC. An interpretation of the model is: holding the other parameters constant: as MEDUC (Mothers Education)increases by 1 unit, the baby birth weight is estimated to increase by 20.7g, as MAGER (Mothers Single Years of Age) increases by 1 unit, the baby birth weight is estimated to increase by 4.158g, as WTGAIN (Weight Gain) increases by 1 unit, the baby birth weight is estimated to increase by 3.708g.
